## Overview

Unpredictable cattle movement in South Sudan contributes to local conflict, resource scarcity, and humanitarian risk. There is currently no reliable, real-time way to understand where cattle are located or how they are likely to move over time.

This project explores how **AI-based mapping and predictive modeling**, using **open-source satellite imagery and environmental data**, can be used to **detect, predict, and visualize cattle presence and movement**.

Version **v3** represents a major milestone. It transitions the project from rule-based inference to a **trainable neural network** with persistent learning, while maintaining a clean, interpretable visual interface.

This system **does not use GPS collars or direct tracking**. All predictions rely on **satellite imagery and environmental signals**, aligned with real-world constraints.

